explanation:
For determining whether the memset in OS_SocketOpen can access beyond the bounds of the object, the analyzer needs the following symbols and why:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: the macro influences control flow (early abort on NULL sock_id); need to confirm it does not affect stream/memset behavior or introduce side-effects relevant to object validity.
- OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew: this routine produces the token and guarantees allocation/validation semantics. Its behavior determines whether the token returned actually references a valid element in the stream table (i.e. memory that can be written with memset).
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: the object-type argument passed to OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew selects which table is allocated from (must be the stream table); required to confirm that the token refers to an OS_stream entry.
- OS_object_token_t: the token type definition (fields and semantics, e.g. index/flags) is needed to interpret how the token maps to a table entry and whether it can be used safely with OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: this macro/function maps a token to a pointer. Its definition is essential to verify that the returned pointer points into OS_stream_table and to understand any additional pointer arithmetic done there.
- OS_stream_table: the actual storage (array or pointer) backing the stream records. The analyzer must know its allocation size and layout to ensure memset size does not exceed the actual element size or table bounds.
- OS_stream_internal_record_t: the concrete struct type used with sizeof in memset; its definition gives the exact number of bytes written and whether it contains flexible arrays or other fields that affect size.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: commonly used in table macros to convert token to an array index. Its behavior and bounds checks (if any) are needed to ensure the index is valid for OS_stream_table before memset occurs.
- OS_SUCCESS: the value checked to enter the block; needed to reason about control flow and whether the code path that performs memset can be reached (i.e. that token/stream are valid).
- memset: the standard library function used; include its expected semantics (writes n bytes starting at pointer) so the analyzer can match the computed sizeof against the actual object size and ensure no out-of-bounds write.

Providing these symbols (definitions/prototypes/macros/constants) lets the next agent determine whether the pointer returned by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET points to an object at least sizeof(OS_stream_internal_record_t) bytes long and whether any indexing/mapping steps can produce out-of-range addresses, which is required to assess MISRA C rule compliance for string.h memory functions.
